A black box in your car?
While the planners of the U.S. road network have difficulty finding the money needed to repair the motorway infrastructure in decreption, many are those who come up with a solution in the form of a small black box that is fixed above the dashboard of your car.
The aircraft, which record all the miles through a motorist and transmit the information to officials, are at the heart of a controversial attempt in Washington and in the government planning offices to revise the obsolete financing system for major American roads.
The sector generally without interest in the planning of major axes has suddenly led to a strong lively debate and lively alliances.
Libertarians have joined environmental groups to press for the government to use small boxes to keep track of the miles you travel, and possibly of the road you travel on, and then use the information to write a bill.
The Tea Party is landed.
The American Civil Liberties Union is also very concerned and expresses its concern about the protection of privacy.
And while members of Congress are unable to agree on whether to continue, several States have not waited.
They are looking for how, over the next decade, they will be able to switch to a system that allows drivers to pay according to the number of miles across.
Thousands of motorists have already boarded these black boxes, sometimes equipped with a GPS surveillance system, for an experimental shift.
This is really essential for our nation.
"It's not as if we had the choice," said Hasan Ikhrata, CEO of the Southern California Association of Governments, who expects the state to begin recording the miles that each California car will be travelling by 2025.
There will be a change in the way we pay these taxes.
The technology is here to do it.
The pressure comes from the fact that the country's Highway Trust Fund, funded by the American pump taxes, is financially dry.
Americans don't buy as much gasoline as they did before.
Cars can travel more than miles with a gallon.
The federal tax itself, which is 18.4 cents per gallon, has not increased for 20 years.
Political men are reluctant to increase the tax, even by 1 cent, while gasoline prices are high.
"The gasoline tax is simply not tenable," said Lee Munnich, a transportation policy specialist at the University of Minnesota.
His State has recently installed tracers on 500 cars to test a mile payment system.
"It turns out to be the most logical alternative in the long term," he said.
Wonks calls this a mileage usage fee.
It is not surprising that the idea seduces the urban Liberals, as taxes could be used to change driving habits so as to reduce the build-up and emissions of gases, for example.
California planners are interested in the system as they develop strategies to achieve the objectives set out in the State's ambitious climate warming laws.
But representative Bill Shuster (R-Pa.), Chairman of the Transport Committee of the House of Representatives, said that he also considered it the most viable alternative in the long term.
The open market supporters of the Reason Foundation also appreciate the idea of getting drivers paid on the mile.
"It's not just a tax drowning in a big black hole," said Adrian Moore, policy vice president at the Reason Foundation.
People pay more directly for their benefits.
The movement is also supported by two former U.S. Transport Secretaries who, in a 2011 report, urged Congress to move on to the mile payment.
The U.S. Senate approved a $90 million pilot project last year, which would have covered about 10,000 cars.
But the Presidency of the Chamber killed the proposal, responding to the concerns of rural legislators representing voters who must travel many miles every day to go to their work or in the city.
However, several States and large cities are making progress on their side.
The most determined is Oregon, which has mobilized 5,000 drivers to lead the country's most important experience.
These motorists will soon pay the state for the cost of kilometres instead of gasoline taxes.
Nevada has already completed a pilot project.
New York City is considering one.
Illinois is testing a limited number of trucks.
And the I-95 coalition, which includes 17 agencies involved in road transport in States along the coast is American (including Maryland, Pennsylvania, Virginia and Florida) investigates how it could implement change.
The concept is not a universal success.
In Nevada, where about 50 volunteer motorists had recently equipped their car with a device, the drivers were concerned that the government could follow their own actions and actions.
"Big Brother's concerns and these kinds of things are a major problem," said Alauddin Khan, who directs performance strategic management to the Nevada Transport Department.
It's not something people want.
From the beginning of the test, the Nevada ACLU warned on its site: "It would be relatively easy to convert these devices into full localization devices."
There is no need to build a huge and overwhelming technological infrastructure that will inevitably be expanded to keep records of people's day-to-day departures and arrivals.
Nevada is one of the few States that are now going to find affordable technology that would allow the State to know how many miles a car travels, but not knowing the exact time or place.
If we can do this, Khan added, the citizens will be more comfortable.
The search for this technology has led some state agencies to use a small start-up from California named True Mileage.
Originally, the company was not intended to assist motorists who pay taxes to States.
She was seeking to enter the emerging car insurance market, in which drivers would pay according to their mileage.
But the devices it tests have liked the planners of the major axes because they do not use the GPS and provide a limited amount of information, periodically downloaded by modem.
"People will be more inclined to do this if you don't record their speed and don't locate them," said Ryan Morrison, Director General of True Mileage.
Major errors have been made in the pilot programmes of some States.
