They may still choose not to have a device at all, preferring instead to pay a package based on the average number of miles traveled by all residents of the state.
Other States hope to sell the concept to suspicious citizens by enabling devices to do more, rather than enough.
In New York City, transport officials are seeking to develop a taxing device that would also be equipped to pay parking fees, provide "payment-to-conduct" insurance, and create a set of real-time speed data from other drivers that drivers could use to avoid traffic jams.
"Car drivers would be encouraged to participate because of the benefits offered by the system," said a document on urban planning.
However, some transport planners wondered whether the entire debate on mile payment was simply a huge diversion.
