Scientists have just highlighted how the movements of a dog's tail are related to its mood.
Previous studies had revealed that happy dogs were moving their tail further to the right (from the dog's point of view), while nervous dogs were moving it further to the left.
But now scientists say that dogs can detect and respond to these subtle differences.
Professor Georgio Vallortigara, a neuroscientist at the University of Trento, said: "Everyone knows that in humans, the left side and the right side of the brain are involved differently in the stimuli that awaken positive or negative emotions."
Here, we tried to see what was in other species.
He added that as in man, in dogs the right side of the brain was responsible for the movement to the left and vice versa, and that the two hemispheres played a different role in the emotions.
To learn more about how dogs react to tail movements disordered by other dogs, researchers followed animals watching films where other dogs were found.
They measured the heart rate of the animals and analyzed their behavior.
It will probably not take long before we understand why their tail sometimes goes from one side to another.
Professor Vallortigara explained: "We presented to dogs films featuring other dogs – either a naturalist version or a silhouette to avoid any other confusion factors – and we were able to betray the tail movement and present it as going more left or right."
When the animals saw a dog without expression move the tail to the right (from the point of view of the dog that removes the tail), they remained perfectly relaxed.
But when they found a tail turning mainly to the left (again from the dog's point of view that removes the tail), their heart rate accelerated and they looked anxious.
Professor Vallortigara said that he did not think that the dogs deliberately communicated with each other through these movements.
Rather, he thinks that dogs know by experience which movements they should or should not worry about.
He added: "If you meet other dogs several times and notice that, most of the time, the movement of their tail to one side is associated with a more friendly attitude and that the right side leads to a less friendly attitude, you will react on the basis of this experience."
Researchers indicate that the results could allow owners, veterinarians and breeders to better understand the emotions of their animals.
The dog behavior expert John Bradshaw, a visiting professor at the School of Veterinary Sciences at the University of Bristol, stated that this was not the first study to examine the importance of the left and right in the canine species.
Last year, a team at Lincoln University discovered that dogs turned their heads to the left when they looked at an aggressive dog and to the right when it was a happy dog.
And in another scientific study conducted by Victoria University in Canada, he said: "The dogs went more easily to a robot dog when its tail moved to the left rather than to the right, instead of becoming anxious – the opposite of what is in the Italian study."
He indicated that differences could come from the fact that dogs who participated in different studies did not fully consider animals of films or robot dogs as dogs.
A study on how dogs react to real dogs could be useful, he explained.
"Although many elements, recorded in different mammals, indicate that both sides of the brain are used for different purposes, many details still need to be specified – and dogs are no exception," he said.
However, given the ease with which their behaviours can be recorded, it will probably not take long before we understand why their tail sometimes moves on one side and sometimes on the other.
