For 21 years, Georges Bwelle watched his sick father alter the periods of consciousness and unconsciousness and go to hospitals that were not equipped to help him.
Jamef Bwelle was injured in a car accident in 1981 near Yaoundé, the capital of Cameroon.
At first, he had only a broken arm, but he contracted an infection that spread to his brain, creating a hematoma that he was going to carry the sequelae the rest of his life.
"There were no neurosurgeons in Cameroon," said Georges Bwelle.
We would have taken him abroad if we had had enough money.
Instead, Dr. Bwelle spent years accompanying his father in crowded clinics and hospitals to obtain any treatment he could benefit from.
"It's not easy," says Mr. Bwelle.
You can leave the house at five o'clock, yell at the hospital to be the first, and you're not the first.
There are a lot of patients.
People can die because they wait too long.
The situation has not changed much since Dr. Bwelle's father died in 2002.
In Cameroon, there are only one doctor per 5,000 inhabitants, according to the World Health Organization.
As a comparison, the ratio in the United States is 1 doctor per 413 inhabitants.
And even if they could see a doctor, many Cameroonians could not pay for the consultation.
Two out of five people in the country live below the poverty line, and nearly three-quarters of the country's health expenditures are incurred in the private sector.
"The only problem they have is poverty," explained Dr. Bwelle.
And because of poverty, they cannot enjoy life.
After seeing his father and all his fellow countrymen suffer, Dr. Bwelle was determined to try to change the course of things.
Dr. Georges Bwelle and his volunteer team performed more than 700 surgical acts free of charge last year.
He became a doctor himself, working as a vascular surgeon at Yaoundé Central Hospital.
And he created a non-profit humanitarian association, ASCOVIME, which goes to rural areas during weekends to provide free health care.
Since 2008, he and his group of volunteers have assisted almost 32,000 people.
Almost every Friday, with about 30 people, they start in vans after fixing medical equipment on the roof and cross difficult terrains to get to the villages that need help most.
Chance doesn't always follow them.
They have repeatedly had to push vehicles to cross rivers or muddy tracks.
But when they arrive, they are received as heroes: the community organizes a party, singing and dancing and offers them the best available accommodation.
In these villages, free health care is a good reason to celebrate, and Dr. Bwelle – with his great smile and overwhelming energy – is more than happy to join the festivities.
The next morning, the team began to receive hundreds of patients.
"We receive 500 people on each visit," said Mr. Bwelle.
Sometimes they live 60 km from the village, and they come on foot.
In this traveling hospital, various health care is provided.
Many people receive treatment against malaria, tuberculosis, malnutrition, diabetes, parasites and sexually transmitted diseases.
Others may receive beckons, a pair of glasses collected or a free birth certificate – document necessary to go to school, but many poor families simply cannot afford to buy it.
In the evening, the practical team of simple surgical acts under local anesthesia.
The operations are usually performed in a school, a mayor or a house; after the intervention, the patient gets up and goes to the wake-up room to leave his place to the next person.
Thanks to the lighting of the generator, the operating room and sterilization of the equipment, Dr. Bwelle and his volunteers work until the first hours of Sunday morning.
It's an exciting rhythm, but village musicians generally help the team remain motivated.
"They hit drums all night long to keep us awake so that we can continue to work," explained Bwelle.
On Sunday, the team returns to town, tired but proud of the work she has done.
The group, composed of Cameroonian doctors and medical students, performed 700 surgical acts free of charge last year, and he knows that their presence can make all the difference for those they help.
One man explained that the free operation he had undergone to treat a hernia would allow him to work again.
"It will change my future and that of my family," said the man.
In addition to living this traveling hospital and working as a surgeon at the hospital, Dr. Bwelle also works at night in private medical offices around Yaoundé.
It is this second job, he explains, which finances 60% of its association; the rest is covered by private donations.
"I don't know when he's asleep," said Katie O'Malley, a second year medical student from Drexel University in Philadelphia and volunteer in Dr. Bwelle's group.
He's always in the hospital or trying to find money for his association so he can run these campaigns.
For medical students and nursing students such as Katie O'Malley, who come from the United States and Europe to join Mr.Bwelle in his missions, this is an opportunity to learn in the field they don't have at home.
"We were able to participate in operations to help drain the blood or pass the instruments to Dr. Bwell," explained Ms. O'Malley.
It's not something you have a chance to do in America when you're a medical student in the second year.
Volunteer students generally pay for their trip to Cameroon, and often arrive with collected medical equipment.
But once in Yaoundé, their pensions, transportation and education are taken care of by Dr. Bwelle.
"He is a hero, there is no doubt," said Katie O'Malley.
He gives his life for this association, and his desire to help the Cameroonian people is not close to extinction.
For Dr. Bwelle, the relatively constant workload is not a challenge.
Helping others to live happily by keeping his promise to his father is something that brings him immense joy.
"I am so happy when I do this work," added Mr. Bwelle.
And I think of my father.
I hope he sees what I'm doing.
To make people laugh and relieve pain are the reasons why I do that.
